    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>St James' Sqre Friday Evg. 24th Jany</p>
      <p>My mother is to forward you a letter of mine that I wrote to her this afternoon. This letter will explain the particulars which make it doubtful, at least, if I shall return to Ockham for the next 2 or 3 days. I have long been much troubled by pains &amp; inconvenience, especially after riding; &amp; it appears there is indeed cause enough.</p>
      <p>As there is nothing to take me back particularly, at this moment, I have the less hesitation in staying on here.</p>
      <p>Dr Locock is quite delighted with my general health; but this local tendency is a troublesome thing.--</p>
      <p>I suppose I am not, in fact, a very strong person, &amp; am so delicately made as to be liable first to one derangement &amp; then to another.--</p>
      <p>I was glad of your letter, my Dear, which the Hen forwarded to me here this morning. The only reason why I had not written on Weddy, was that I had in truth nothing to say, was rather tired too, &amp; also much occupied by Charlotte Barrington &amp; Mr Burton.--</p>
      <p>If you would [two words crossed out] [entire line crossed out] [most of line crossed out] send me a letter tomorrow by the 3 o'clock coach, it would be a great relief to me. I shall otherwise be feeling very anxious, as there is no post here on Sunday Morg. Wilson has often sent</p>
      <p>up letters for me by that coach, &amp; they are delivered without fail.--</p>
      <p>I have seen the E. Duppas, who are staying in Town.</p>
      <p>I don't think I have more to say. I am very well; generally speaking.--</p>
    </div></body>
